# Code Standards

## Product specification

Treat **`Reglens - Regualtory Tech.md`** (repository root) as the authoritative product specification. Before planning or implementing non-trivial changes, read the relevant sections so work serves product goals (scope, personas, workflows, architecture intent) and stays consistent with the PRD.

If a change would diverge from the spec, call that out and propose the smallest adjustment that stays aligned—or ask the user before expanding scope.

## Core Principle

Always find the **simplest, most minimal correct solution** before writing any code.

Before implementing anything, ask: "What is the least amount of code that solves this correctly?"

Prefer editing existing code over adding new code. Prefer small, focused changes over rewrites.

## DRY

Do not copy-paste logic or configuration when a single shared place (function, module, constant) is clearer. Extract duplication only when it reduces real maintenance cost; avoid premature abstraction for one-off cases.

## Testing

Write tests that assert observable behavior and important edge cases, not implementation details. Keep tests focused and fast; prefer deterministic data and isolated units or slices over brittle full-stack coupling unless an integration test is explicitly the goal.

## Builds and migrations

Do **not** run build commands (for example `mvn`, `gradle`, `npm run build`, `pnpm build`, `docker compose build`) or database migration commands (for example Flyway/Liquibase CLI, `alembic upgrade`, raw SQL migrate scripts) when making routine code changes.

Only run builds or migrations if the user explicitly asks you to run them, or if they are strictly required to verify a change the user requested (and then say why before running).
